So, what I THINK you are asking, is why does the linked list node structure definition have a pointer to another node rather than just including the struct.

First of all you code should declare the pointer to next as `struct node *next` as below.

    struct node {
       int data;
       struct node *next;
    };

If instead of a pointer the next field was another node structure, then evey node would contain another node, and that node would contain another note, and so on.  A node struct would be infinately large.  It must be a pointer, and that is the point of a &#39;linked&#39; list - it links to another node, it does not contain it.

If you declare a struct within another struct, it is literally contained within it.  This is why a recursive struct definition is not allowed.

